Question

Early probability theory explored what happens when you roll multiple dice. They did not have computers to run large simulations. We do.

In table-top role-playing games, it is common to use dice notation. I simulated 1000 repetitions of rolling 11d6+5d20. In each repetition, I rolled 11 six-sided dice and 5 twenty-sided dice and added up all the numbers to get a value. To analyze the distribution of these values, you will find percentiles using nearest rank method.

Solution

  • Get your data into column A of a spreadsheet, from A1 to A1000.
  • Sort your data using Data, Sort sheet, Sort sheet by column A.
  • Calculate the indices of the percentiles:
    • For the 2.5th percentile: \(0.025\cdot 1000=25\)
    • For the 16th percentile: \(0.16\cdot 1000=160\)
    • For the 50th percentile: \(0.6\cdot 1000=500\)
    • For the 84th percentile: \(0.84\cdot 1000=840\)
    • For the 97.5th percentile: \(0.975\cdot 1000=975\)
  • Find the values at those rows.
    • The value in cell A\(25\) should be \(64\).
    • The value in cell A\(160\) should be \(77\).
    • The value in cell A\(500\) should be \(91\).
    • The value in cell A\(840\) should be \(106\).
    • The value in cell A\(975\) should be \(119\).

You can see answers as the color changes in the sorted list below.


I’ve produced a dot plot that helps visualize these percentiles.


You might notice the five answers are spaced evenly-ish.

\[77-64=13\] \[91-77=14\] \[106-91=15\] \[119-106=13\]

This is not a coincidence. Because each repetition of the simulation involves adding a bunch of independent random variables, we expect the output values to be normally distributed.

If you’ve studied a lot of probability, you might know about standard deviation. If you look up discrete uniform distribution, you can find the formula for the standard deviation for a 6-sided die or a 20-sided die.

\[\mathrm{SD(1d6)} = \sqrt{\frac{6^2-1}{12}} \approx 1.708\] \[\mathrm{SD(1d20)} = \sqrt{\frac{20^2-1}{12}} \approx 5.766\]

If you’ve REALLY studied probability, you might know one of the most important reasons we use standard deviation: if random variables X and Y are independent, then \(\mathrm{SD(X+Y)=\sqrt{SD(X)^2+SD(Y)^2}}\). This implies the following:

\[\mathrm{SD(11d6+5d20)} = \sqrt{11\cdot1.708^2+5\cdot5.766^2} \approx 14.1\]

To learn more, read about the central limit theorem and the 68-95-99.7 rule.
